    rationale: "An ABI >1.40 indicates noncompressible vessels \u2014 a finding common in diabetes and chronic kidney disease, where medial calcification (M\u00f6nckeberg sclerosis) makes arterial walls rigid and incompressible by the blood pressure cuff. The cuff cannot occlude the artery, so the measured ankle pressure is artifactually elevated, producing a falsely high ABI. This result does not rule out PAD; in fact, these patients often have significant PAD. Alternative diagnostic methods such as toe-brachial index (TBI) or pulse volume recordings should be used, as digital arteries are less affected by calcification. An ABI <0.90 diagnoses PAD; ABI <0.50 indicates severe PAD.",
