    rationale: "In normal, compliant arteries, the systolic pressure wave amplifies as it travels distally due to wave reflection from arterial branch points and the progressive decrease in arterial compliance. This phenomenon \u2014 pulse pressure amplification \u2014 results in ankle systolic pressures that are equal to or slightly higher than brachial pressures, giving a normal ABI of 0.90\u20131.40. In PAD, proximal stenoses attenuate the pressure wave, reducing ankle pressure and lowering the ABI. Ankle artery diameter is not larger than brachial arteries. Hydrostatic effects are negligible in the supine position. Sympathetic tone does not selectively elevate tibial artery pressure.",
